Project name: DailyFlow

Project overview:
DailyFlow is a web application that helps users manage their schedule, routines, and wellbeing in one place.

The full product is planned to include:
- onboarding questionnaire
- calendar screen
- meals and grocery planning
- workouts
- stress and break recommendations
- overview / weekly summary

Main integrations and infrastructure:
- Frontend: React
- Backend: Python on AWS Lambda
- Authentication: Amazon Cognito
- Database: DynamoDB
- Hosting: AWS Amplify
- External integrations: Google Calendar
- Future integrations: OpenAI and Apple Watch / HRV-based data

Current implemented state:
- AWS Cognito is already connected in the frontend
- Sign up and Log in already work
- A frontend questionnaire screen already exists
- DynamoDB tables already exist, including Users
- The project is now entering the Calendar milestone
- Google Calendar integration setup has started conceptually and should now be implemented incrementally

Final product goal:
The final product should support a full user flow where a user signs in, completes an onboarding questionnaire, connects Google Calendar, chooses which calendars to expose, syncs availability, receives personalized suggestions, and manages their schedule through the platform.

Current milestone scope:
For now, focus only on the current milestone:
- onboarding questionnaire refinement if explicitly requested
- calendar screen
- Google Calendar connection
- Google OAuth flow preparation and implementation
- calendar connection UI states
- fetching the user calendar list after successful connection
- allowing the user to choose which Google calendars to expose
- preparing the availability sync flow
- DailyFlow calendar flow preparation

Calendar milestone product direction:
- The app should include a Calendar screen
- This screen should include a Connect Google Calendar entry point
- After connection, the app should be able to fetch the user's calendar list
- The user will choose which calendars to expose to the app
- The system will later use those selected calendars to derive busy blocks
- Busy blocks should represent occupied time from the selected calendars
- The sync window should be one month ahead
- The system should later create and use a separate Google calendar named DailyFlow
- DailyFlow events and busy blocks are different concepts and should remain logically separated

Important:
- Work incrementally and in small steps
- Prefer building the UI skeleton first, then connecting backend logic, then adding sync logic
- It is allowed to implement frontend calendar screens and minimal backend support for Google Calendar when explicitly requested
- It is allowed to implement Google OAuth start and callback flow when explicitly requested
- It is allowed to prepare or implement the basic calendar list fetch after connection when explicitly requested
- Do not implement Meals, Workouts, Stress, Overview, OpenAI, or Apple Watch logic unless explicitly requested
- Do not invent recommendation logic yet
- Do not implement advanced scheduling logic yet
- Do not implement full sync engines, background jobs, or complex automation unless explicitly requested
- Do not add unnecessary architecture changes
- Do not rewrite unrelated parts of the app
- Keep the implementation aligned with the existing project structure and current milestone only

Implementation guidance:
- Keep the code simple and minimal
- Do not over-engineer
- Use clear and scalable structure
- Prefer readable components and small focused functions
- Do not add unnecessary libraries
- Use English for code, file names, and comments
- Reuse the existing project structure as much as possible
- Only create or update files that are necessary for the requested task
- If environment variables are needed, clearly list their exact names
- If backend routes are needed, keep them minimal and focused
- If placeholder logic is used, make it light and easy to replace later

Working style:
- Before generating code, first explain the plan
- Before generating code, list which files will be created or updated
- Keep changes scoped to the requested step only
- Prefer production-oriented structure, but implement only the smallest useful piece each time
- When something is not implemented yet, use a simple placeholder rather than inventing a full system